title: `BucketFullException` has been removed from pyrate-limiter >= 4.0.0
stack_trace: `BucketFullException` has been removed from pyrate-limiter >=4.0.0 see changelog [here](https://github.com/vutran1710/PyrateLimiter/blob/70b6f5822ce9e0fed49bfd22acc45515d5d845e2/CHANGELOG.md?plain=1#L14).

However, it's exported in the requests_ratelimiter `__init__.py` file [here](https://github.com/JWCook/requests-ratelimiter/blob/cbdf7b22e8ff6f68fd2f5b867dc3c6ad33fad1d6/requests_ratelimiter/__init__.py#L13), which can lead to unexpected crashes.
knowledge_text: `BucketFullException` has been removed from pyrate-limiter >=4.0.0 see changelog [here](https://github.com/vutran1710/PyrateLimiter/blob/70b6f5822ce9e0fed49bfd22acc45515d5d845e2/CHANGELOG.md?plain=1#L14). However, it's exported in the requests_ratelimiter `__init__.py` file [here](https://github.com/JWCook/requests-ratelimiter/blob/cbdf7b22e8ff6f68fd2f5b867dc3c6ad33fad1d6/requests_ratelimiter/__init__.py#L13), which can lead to unexpected crashes. To replicate: ``` from requests_ratelimiter import BucketFullException ``` or ``` from requests_ratelimiter import * ``` Expected error: ``` >>> from requests_ratelimiter import BucketFullException Traceback (most recent call last): File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module> from requests_ratelimiter import BucketFullException ImportError: cannot import name 'BucketFullException' from 'requests_ratelimiter' (/Users/****/dev/requests-ratelimiter/requests_ratelimiter/__init__.py) ```

title: KeyError in _handle_message crashes _listen task after reconnect
stack_trace: In [`channel.py#L528`](https://github.com/supabase/supabase-py/blob/v2.27.3/src/realtime/src/realtime/_async/channel.py#L528), `dict.pop()` is called without a default value:

If a `ReplyMessage` arrives with a `ref` that is not in `messages_waiting_for_ack`, this raises a `KeyError`. Since `_listen` in `client.py` only catches `ConnectionClosedError`, the unhandled `KeyError` kills the `_listen` task entirely, making the connection unrecoverable.

This is related to #1311 (fixed in #1346). The reconnect logic was fixed to not unsubscribe before rejoining, but `messages_waiting_for_ack` can still contain stale refs after a reconnect, causing this crash.
2026-02-09 20:34:06,910 - ERROR - WebSocket connection closed with code: 1006, reason:
2026-02-09 20:34:17,351 - ERROR - join push timeout for channel realtime:gateways
2026-02-09 20:34:54,379 - ERROR - Fatal error on SSL transport
During handling of the above exception, another exception occurred:
self._fatal_error(exc, 'Fatal write error on socket transport')
2026-02-09 20:34:54,383 - ERROR - Task exception was never retrieved
The `KeyError` crashed the `_listen` task, which prevented the rejoin response from being processed. The channel got permanently stuck in `joining` state.
Suggested fix — use `pop` with a default value:
Run the snippet above and wait for a WebSocket disconnection (close code 1006). The `_listen` task will crash with a `KeyError` when processing a reply with a stale ref during reconnection.
knowledge_text: ### Describe the bug In [`channel.py#L528`](https://github.com/supabase/supabase-py/blob/v2.27.3/src/realtime/src/realtime/_async/channel.py#L528), `dict.pop()` is called without a default value: ```python if message.ref and (push := self.messages_waiting_for_ack.pop(message.ref)): ``` If a `ReplyMessage` arrives with a `ref` that is not in `messages_waiting_for_ack`, this raises a `KeyError`. Since `_listen` in `client.py` only catches `ConnectionClosedError`, the unhandled `KeyError` kills the `_listen` task entirely, making the connection unrecoverable. This is related to #1311 (fixed in #1346). The reconnect logic was fixed to not unsubscribe before rejoining, but `messages_waiting_for_ack` can still contain stale refs after a reconnect, causing this crash. Logs: ``` 2026-02-09 20:33:39,317 - INFO - channel=joined ws=1 close_code=None close_reason=None 2026-02-09 20:34:04,327 - INFO - channel=joined ws=1 close_code=None close_reason=None 2026-02-09 20:34:06,910 - ERROR - WebSocket connection closed with code: 1006, reason: 2026-02-09 20:34:17,351 - ERROR - join push timeout for channel realtime:gateways 2026-02-09 20:34:17,352 - WARNING - subscription status=TIMED_OUT err=None 2026-02-09 20:34:29,330 - INFO - channel=joining ws=1 close_code=None close_reason=None 2026-02-09 20:34:54,338 - INFO - channel=joining ws=1 close_code=None close_reason=None 2026-02-09 20:34:54,379 - ERROR - Fatal error on SSL transport Traceback (most recent call last): File "/usr/lib/python3.10/asyncio/selector_events.py", line 924, in write n = self._sock.send(data) OSError: [Errno 9] Bad file descriptor During handling of the above exception, another exception occurred: Traceback (most recent call last): File "/usr/lib/python3.10/asyncio/sslproto.py", line 690, in _process_write_backlog self._transport.write(chunk) File "/usr/lib/python3.10/asyncio/selector_events.py", line 930, in write self._fatal_error(exc, 'Fatal write error on socket transport') File "/usr/lib/python3.10/asyncio

title: Connection refused error when running interactiveSim.py with native build on WSL2 Ubuntu 24
stack_trace: I'm experiencing a "Connection refused" error when trying to run the interactive simulator with native firmware build on WSL2. The simulator successfully opens 3 node windows via XLaunch, but fails to establish TCP connections to the meshtasticd instances after ~5 seconds.
- XLaunch (VcXsrv Windows X Server) (config -> multiple windows, start no client, Disable access control on)
- XLaunch opens 3 terminal windows (visible on Windows desktop)
- Manual execution of single meshtasticd instance works fine
- After ~5 seconds, the following error occurs, like this one
Error: Could not connect to native program: [Errno 111] Connection refused
During handling of the above exception, another exception occurred:
knowledge_text: ### Description I'm experiencing a "Connection refused" error when trying to run the interactive simulator with native firmware build on WSL2. The simulator successfully opens 3 node windows via XLaunch, but fails to establish TCP connections to the meshtasticd instances after ~5 seconds. ### Environments - Windows 11 (Host) - WSL2 with Ubuntu 24.04 - XLaunch (VcXsrv Windows X Server) (config -> multiple windows, start no client, Disable access control on) ### Steps - Build native firmware `cd ~/firmware` `pio run -e native` - Verify meshtasticd runs manually `~/firmware/.pio/build/native/meshtasticd -p 4403` - Run interactive simulator `python3 interactiveSim.py 3 -p ~/firmware/.pio/build/native/meshtasticd` ### Result - Tkinter successfully creates 3 node windows - XLaunch opens 3 terminal windows (visible on Windows desktop) - Manual execution of single meshtasticd instance works fine - After ~5 seconds, the following error occurs, like this one Booting nodes... title: Duplicate Tags in File Meta Cause Exception in dcmwrite

If the DICOM file is considered invalid due to duplicate file meta tags, it should generate an exception on read, not on write.
The following code snippet using the attached file will reproduce the exception:
NameError: name 'BytesIO' is not defined. Did you mean: 'bytes'?
TypeError: encoding without a string argument

TypeError: With tag (0002,0016) got exception: encoding without a string argument
TypeError: encoding without a string argument
The following code snippet will eliminate the exception:
Please use the `pydicom.env_info` module (available in **pydicom 2 or later**)
to gather information about your environment and paste it into the issue:

title: SyntaxWarning for await expession
stack_trace: Now python has warned for const expression that impossible to successfully executed:
<python-input-2>:1: SyntaxWarning: 'int' object is not callable; perhaps you missed a comma?
<python-input-3>:1: SyntaxWarning: 'int' object is not subscriptable; perhaps you missed a comma?
This feature want to enable the warning for await expressions:
asyncio REPL 3.14.2 (tags/v3.14.2:df79316, Dec  5 2025, 17:18:21) [MSC v.1944 64 bit (AMD64)] on win32

As I have known, there is no literal constant type that support for await (int, bool, float, complex, str, list, tuple, dict, set, ellipsis) so if there is only a constant after await we can safely warn it.
### Has this already been discussed elsewhere?
This is a minor feature, which does not need previous discussion elsewhere
### Links to previous discussion of this feature:
knowledge_text: # Feature or enhancement ### Proposal: Now python has warned for const expression that impossible to successfully executed: ```python >>> 1() <python-input-2>:1: SyntaxWarning: 'int' object is not callable; perhaps you missed a comma? Traceback (most recent call last): File "<python-input-2>", line 1, in <module> 1() ~^^ TypeError: 'int' object is not callable >>> 1[2] <python-input-3>:1: SyntaxWarning: 'int' object is not subscriptable; perhaps you missed a comma? Traceback (most recent call last): File "<python-input-3>", line 1, in <module> 1[2] ~^^^ TypeError: 'int' object is not subscriptable ``` This feature want to enable the warning for await expressions: ```python asyncio REPL 3.14.2 (tags/v3.14.2:df79316, Dec 5 2025, 17:18:21) [MSC v.1944 64 bit (AMD64)] on win32 Use "await" directly instead of "asyncio.run()". Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information. >>> import asyncio >>> await 1 <python-input-0>:1: SyntaxWarning: 'int' object can't be awaited Traceback (most recent call last): File "C:\Users\hh180\AppData\Local\Programs\Python\Python314\Lib\concurrent\futures\_base.py", line 450, in result return self.__get_result() ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^^ File "C:\Users\hh180\AppData\Local\Programs\Python\Python314\Lib\concurrent\futures\_base.py", line 395, in __get_result raise self._exception File "<python-input-0>", line 1, in <module> await 1 TypeError: 'int' object can't be awaited ``` As I have known, there is no literal constant type that support for await (int, bool, float, complex, str, list, tuple, dict, set, ellipsis) so if there is only a constant after await we can safely warn it. ### Has this already been discussed elsewhere? This is a minor feature, which does not need previous discussion elsewhere ### Links to previous discussion of this feature: _No response_ <!-- gh-linked-prs --> ### Linked PRs * gh-144271 <!-- /gh-linked-prs -->

`LintResult`-klassen saknar attributet `fuzzy_count`, men `main()` försöker läsa det på rad 650.
Lägg till `fuzzy_count` i `LintResult`-klassen eller ta bort/villkora utskriften.
knowledge_text: ## Beskrivning När l10n-lint körs kraschar programmet med följande fel: ``` AttributeError: 'LintResult' object has no attribute 'fuzzy_count' ``` ## Stacktrace ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "/Users/bosse/.local/bin/l10n-lint", line 664, in <module> main() File "/Users/bosse/.local/bin/l10n-lint", line 650, in main vprint(_(" Fuzzy: {count}").format(count=result.fuzzy_count)) AttributeError: 'LintResult' object has no attribute 'fuzzy_count' ``` ## Orsak `LintResult`-klassen saknar attributet `fuzzy_count`, men `main()` försöker läsa det på rad 650. ## Förslag till fix Lägg till `fuzzy_count` i `LintResult`-klassen eller ta bort/villkora utskriften. ## Version Upptäckt 2026-02-04 i lokal installation.

knowledge_text: # Description I am trying to load ontologies that contain ontology imports, such as the [Wine ontology](https://www.w3.org/TR/owl-guide/wine.rdf). However, I am unable to, as the imports cannot be loaded. For information, the Wine ontology imports a food ontology, as shown in the file: ``` <owl:Ontology rdf:about=""> <rdfs:comment>An example OWL ontology</rdfs:comment> <owl:priorVersion> <owl:Ontology rdf:about="http://www.w3.org/TR/2003/CR-owl-guide-20030818/wine"/> </owl:priorVersion> <owl:imports rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/TR/2003/PR-owl-guide-20031209/food"/> <rdfs:comment>Derived from the DAML Wine ontology at http://ontolingua.stanford.edu/doc/chimaera/ontologies/wines.daml Substantially changed, in particular the Region based relations. </rdfs:comment> <rdfs:label>Wine Ontology</rdfs:label> </owl:Ontology> ``` # Code to Reproduce the Error ```python from pathlib import Path from owlapy.owl_ontology import SyncOntology import requests from urllib.parse import urlparse def download_file(url, destination_folder="."): # Get the file name from the URL a = urlparse(url) file_name = Path(destination_folder) / Path(a.path).name # Download the file r = requests.get(url, allow_redirects=True) # Save the file with open(file_name, "wb") as f: f.write(r.content) return file_name def test_load_ontology(): url = "https://www.w3.org/TR/owl-guide/wine.rdf" file_name = download_file(url) ontology = SyncOntology(str(file_name.absolute())) assert len(ontology.get_tbox_axioms()) > 0 assert len(ontology.get_abox_axioms()) > 0 print( f"Loaded ontology from {file_name} with {len(ontology.get_tbox_axioms())} TBox axioms and {len(ontology.get_abox_axioms())} ABox axioms." ) if __name__ == "__main__": test_load_ontology() ``` # Error Traceback ``` (owlapy-env) (base) XXX1@XXX2:~/Dokumente/owl-to-text$ python test_load_ontology.py Warning: SQLite3 version 3.40.0 and 3.41.2 have huge performance regressions; please install version 3.41.1 or 3.42! `scaffold.py` does `import git` (GitPython) at module level (line 8), which immediately tries to locate the `git` binary. If it's not found, GitPython raises an `ImportError`, preventing the entire CLI from loading -- even for commands that have nothing to do with scaffolding.
The above exception was the direct cause of the following exception:
ImportError: Failed to initialize: Bad git executable.
Production containers that use `python:*-slim` images (which don't include git) cannot start the app via `vibetuner run prod`.
Lazy-import `git` inside the scaffold functions that actually use it, rather than at module level. The scaffold module is only needed during development, not at runtime.
Setting `GIT_PYTHON_REFRESH=quiet` in the production environment suppresses the error.
knowledge_text: ## Problem `vibetuner` CLI crashes on startup when the `git` executable is not available in the environment (e.g., production Docker containers using slim base images without git installed). ## Root Cause `vibetuner/cli/__init__.py` unconditionally imports `scaffold_app` from `vibetuner/cli/scaffold.py` at line 14: ```python from vibetuner.cli.scaffold import scaffold_app ``` `scaffold.py` does `import git` (GitPython) at module level (line 8), which immediately tries to locate the `git` binary. If it's not found, GitPython raises an `ImportError`, preventing the entire CLI from loading -- even for commands that have nothing to do with scaffolding. ## Traceback ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "/app/.venv/lib/python3.14/site-packages/git/__init__.py", line 296, in <module> refresh() File "/app/.venv/lib/python3.14/site-packages/git/__init__.py", line 287, in refresh if not Git.refresh(path=path): File "/app/.venv/lib/python3.14/site-packages/git/cmd.py", line 860, in refresh raise ImportError(err) ImportError: Bad git executable. The above exception was the direct cause of the following exception: Traceback (most recent call last): File "/app/.venv/bin/vibetuner", line 4, in <module> from vibetuner.cli import app File "/app/.venv/lib/python3.14/site-packages/vibetuner/cli/__init__.py", line 14, in <module> from vibetuner.cli.scaffold import scaffold_app File "/app/.venv/lib/python3.14/site-packages/vibetuner/cli/scaffold.py", line 8, in <module> import git File "/app/.venv/lib/python3.14/site-packages/git/__init__.py", line 298, in <module> raise ImportError("Failed to initialize: {0}".format(_exc)) from _exc ImportError: Failed to initialize: Bad git executable. ``` ## Impact Production containers that use `python:*-slim` images (which don't include git) cannot start the app via `vibetuner run prod`. ## Suggested Fix Lazy-import `git` inside the scaffold functions that actually use it, rather than at module level. The scaffold module is only needed durin

title: `import` from main script directory succeeds
stack_trace: The official Windows Python distribution raises an error when a script `import`s a module from its own directory. This fork actually imports the module successfully.
Let's say we have a directory `C:\myscript` containing `a.py` and `b.py`.
knowledge_text: ### Bug description: The official Windows Python distribution raises an error when a script `import`s a module from its own directory. This fork actually imports the module successfully. Let's say we have a directory `C:\myscript` containing `a.py` and `b.py`. `a.py`: ```python import b print('success!') ``` `C:\msys64\ucrt64\bin\python.exe --version`: ``` Python 3.14.2 ``` `C:\msys64\ucrt64\bin\python.exe C:\myscript\a.py`: ``` success! ``` `C:\python-3.14.3-embed-amd64\python.exe --version`: ``` Python 3.14.3 ``` `C:\python-3.14.3-embed-amd64\python.exe C:\myscript\a.py`: ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "C:\myscript\a.py", line 1, in <module> import b ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'b' ``` ### CPython versions tested on: 3.14 ### Operating systems tested on: Windows

title: Task Tracker integration fails to initialize in Home Assistant 2026.2: AttributeError: 'LovelaceData' object has no attribute 'mode'
stack_trace: Task Tracker fails to load in HA 2026.2 with the following error:
```Error during setup of component task_tracker: 'LovelaceData' object has no attribute 'mode'
Related to HA change where `mode` is no longer valid with `LovelaceData` in 2026.2 and later, must use `resource_mode` instead. Pre-2026.2 still uses `mode`.
knowledge_text: Task Tracker fails to load in HA 2026.2 with the following error: ```Error during setup of component task_tracker: 'LovelaceData' object has no attribute 'mode' Traceback (most recent call last): File "/usr/src/homeassistant/homeassistant/setup.py", line 425, in _async_setup_component result = await task ^^^^^^^^^^ File "/config/custom_components/task_tracker/__init__.py", line 71, in async_setup await cards.async_register() File "/config/custom_components/task_tracker/frontend/__init__.py", line 27, in async_register if self.lovelace.mode == "storage": ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ AttributeError: 'LovelaceData' object has no attribute 'mode' ``` Related to HA change where `mode` is no longer valid with `LovelaceData` in 2026.2 and later, must use `resource_mode` instead. Pre-2026.2 still uses `mode`.

knowledge_text: ## Summary The `thenvoi_rest` SDK throws a confusing `JSONDecodeError` when the API returns a 429 response with an empty body. While the SDK does eventually raise the correct `ApiError`, the intermediate `JSONDecodeError` traceback is displayed due to Python's exception chaining, creating noisy output. ## Environment - Python 3.12 - thenvoi-sdk-python (latest) - Server returning 429 from AWS ALB with empty body (`Content-Length: 0`) ## Actual Behavior ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File ".../thenvoi_rest/agent_api/raw_client.py", line 2987, in get_agent_me _response_json = _response.json() ... json.decoder.JSONDecodeError: Expecting value: line 1 column 1 (char 0) During handling of the above exception, another exception occurred: Traceback (most recent call last): ... thenvoi_rest.core.api_error.ApiError: status_code: 429, body: ``` ## Expected Behavior A clean `ApiError` with no intermediate exception traceback. ## Root Cause In `raw_client.py` (lines 2955-2990), the code pattern is: ```python try: if 200 <= _response.status_code < 300: return parse_response(_response.json()) if _response.status_code == 401: raise UnauthorizedError(body=_response.json()) if _response.status_code == 403: raise ForbiddenError(body=_response.json()) _response_json = _response.json() # <-- Fails here for 429 with empty body except JSONDecodeError: raise ApiError(...) # Exception chaining shows both tracebacks ``` - 429 doesn't match the explicit handlers, so falls through to JSON parsing - Empty body causes `JSONDecodeError` - Python's exception chaining displays both tracebacks **Note:** `thenvoi_rest` is auto-generated by Fern, so fixes must go in Fern templates. ## Proposed Fix ### Option 1: Fern template fix - Add `from None` (Recommended) ```python except JSONDecodeError: raise ApiError(...) from None # Suppress chained exception ``` ### Option 2: Early exit for error responses ```python if _response.status_code >= 400: try: body = _response.json() except JSONDecodeError:

knowledge_text: ## Problem The GitHub CI action 'VibeEmu Only (Manual)' is currently failing for both DMG and CGB modes due to a `NameError: name 'TestResult' is not defined`. ### Details - **CI Job:** [VibeEmu Only (Manual)](https://github.com/vulcandth/GBEmulatorShootout/actions/runs/21878389825) - **Error Output:** ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "D:\a\GBEmulatorShootout\GBEmulatorShootout\main.py", line 216, in <module> result = emulator.run(test) ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ File "D:\a\GBEmulatorShootout\GBEmulatorShootout\emulators\vibeemu.py", line 150, in run return TestResult(result=result, screenshot=screenshot, startuptime=0, runtime=elapsed) ^^^^^^^^^^ NameError: name 'TestResult' is not defined ``` - **Affected file:** `emulators/vibeemu.py` - **CI triggered by:** running `acid/which.gb` test ROM ## Steps to Reproduce 1. Run the `VibeEmu Only (Manual)` action in GitHub CI. 2. Observe the logs for DMG or CGB test modes. ## Proposed Resolution - Ensure that the `TestResult` class/object is properly imported and defined in `vibeemu.py`. - Review `main.py`, `vibeemu.py`, and related modules to verify the correct scope and import path for `TestResult`. - After fix, re-run the CI action to confirm resolution. --- **Languages:** Python, Assembly **Priority:** High (blocks CI)

title: LDAP bind not attempted if hash verification fails
stack_trace: If the LDAP server does not implement Argon2 hashes and the `argon2.PasswordHasher().verify()` method throws an `InvalidHashError`, Quality-time gives up and does not attempt an LDAP bind.

Solution: `check_password()` should be prepared for any [exception `argon2.PasswordHasher().verify` can throw](https://argon2-cffi.readthedocs.io/en/stable/api.html#argon2.PasswordHasher.verify), log them, and return `False`.
knowledge_text: If the LDAP server does not implement Argon2 hashes and the `argon2.PasswordHasher().verify()` method throws an `InvalidHashError`, Quality-time gives up and does not attempt an LDAP bind. ```console Could not authenticate LDAP user: Traceback (most recent call last): File "/home/server/routes/auth.py", line 110, in verify_user if (password_hash := ldap_user.userPassword.value) and check_password(password_hash, password): ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ File "/home/server/routes/auth.py", line 60, in check_password return argon2.PasswordHasher().verify(password_hash.decode().removeprefix("{ARGON2}"), password) ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ File "/home/server/venv/lib/python3.14/site-packages/argon2/_password_hasher.py", line 256, in verify raise InvalidHashError from None argon2.exceptions.InvalidHashError ``` Solution: `check_password()` should be prepared for any [exception `argon2.PasswordHasher().verify` can throw](https://argon2-cffi.readthedocs.io/en/stable/api.html#argon2.PasswordHasher.verify), log them, and return `False`.

knowledge_text: ### What happened? Whenever attempting to start TensorBoard on the latest OneTrainer in environments where the `setuptools` version >=82.0.0, TensorBoard fails with the error `ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'pkg_resources'`. ### What did you expect would happen? title: Mlflow auth looks for incorrect response
stack_trace: `health_check` method does not properly check for a successful web response
2026-01-30 02:34:26 INFO ✅ Successfully logged in to MLflow. Happy logging!
30-Jan-26 02:34:37 - INFO - Using default logging config without output log file
ConnectionError: Could not connect to MLflow server at https://mlflow.ecmwf.int/. The server may require authentication, did you forget to turn it on?
This occurs because the multiurl library's `response.text` field is the entire HTML document in the response body, which does not equal the literal string "OK".
To check for a successful response, we should just check `response.status_code == 200`.
### What are the steps to reproduce the bug?
- successful authentication at [mlflow.ecmwf.int](https://mlflow.ecmwf.int/) via `anemoi-training mlflow login --url https://mlflow.ecmwf.int/`
ConnectionError: Could not connect to MLflow server at https://mlflow.ecmwf.int/. The server may require authentication, did you forget to turn it on?
knowledge_text: ### What happened? anemoi-training==0.9.0 anemoi-utils==0.4.43 `health_check` method does not properly check for a successful web response [ML flow code at exception](https://github.com/ecmwf/anemoi-utils/blob/12aaadaf0940964238f097c49dddb35ffa3e3fbf/src/anemoi/utils/mlflow/utils.py#L38) ``` if response.text == "OK": ## <----- should be response.status_code == 200 return ``` throws the following ``` 2026-01-30 02:34:26 INFO ✅ Successfully logged in to MLflow. Happy logging! Apptainer> anemoi-training mlflow sync --source {mlflow_logs} --destination https://mlflow.ecmwf.int/ --run-id {run_id} --experiment-name {my_experiment} --verbose 30-Jan-26 02:34:37 - INFO - Using default logging config without output log file Traceback (most recent call last): File "/usr/local/bin/anemoi-training", line 10, in <module> sys.exit(main()) ^^^^^^ File "/usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages/anemoi/training/__main__.py", line 23, in main cli_main(__version__, __doc__, COMMANDS) File "/usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages/anemoi/utils/cli.py", line 266, in cli_main cmd.run(args) File "/usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages/anemoi/training/commands/mlflow.py", line 261, in run **health_check**(args.destination) File "/usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages/anemoi/utils/mlflow/utils.py", line 44, in health_check raise ConnectionError(error_msg) ConnectionError: Could not connect to MLflow server at https://mlflow.ecmwf.int/. The server may require authentication, did you forget to turn it on? ``` This occurs because the multiurl library's `response.text` field is the entire HTML document in the response body, which does not equal the literal string "OK". ## Proposed Solution To check for a successful response, we should just check `response.status_code == 200`. ### What are the steps to reproduce the bug? - anemoi-training==0.9.0 - successful authentication at [mlflow.ecmwf.int](https://mlflow.ecmwf.int/) via `anemoi-training mlflow login --url https://mlflow.ecmwf.int/` - `anemoi-

title: pytest imported unconditionally but is a dev dependency
stack_trace: `typsht._internal.pytest_plugin` is imported in `__init__.py`, which imports `pytest`. but pytest is listed as a dev dependency, not a runtime dependency.
1. add pytest to runtime dependencies, or
2. lazy-import the pytest plugin (only when pytest is available)
option 2 is probably better since not everyone needs the pytest plugin when using the CLI.
knowledge_text: ## problem `typsht._internal.pytest_plugin` is imported in `__init__.py`, which imports `pytest`. but pytest is listed as a dev dependency, not a runtime dependency. this causes `uvx typsht` to fail: ``` $ uvx typsht --file foo.py Traceback (most recent call last): File "/.../typsht/__init__.py", line 5, in <module> from typsht._internal.pytest_plugin import ( File "/.../typsht/_internal/pytest_plugin.py", line 32, in <module> import pytest ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'pytest' ``` ## workaround ```bash uvx --with pytest typsht --file foo.py ``` ## suggested fix either: 1. add pytest to runtime dependencies, or 2. lazy-import the pytest plugin (only when pytest is available) option 2 is probably better since not everyone needs the pytest plugin when using the CLI.

title: PartialModel raises PydanticSerializationError on .model_json_schema with pattern="" in Field definition
stack_trace: A Pydantic Model with a Field(pattern="regex") will raise an "pydantic_core._pydantic_core.PydanticSerializationError: Unable to serialize unknown type: <class 'pydantic._internal._fields._general_metadata_cls.<locals>._PydanticGeneralMetadata'>" exception when calling .model_json_schema() on the class derived with pydantic-partial.create_partial_model
If I remove the "fails" property or add a "default" value to it or remove the "pattern" argument, the code works.
The issue seems to be that the metadata from the "fails" property is converted to a "json_schema_extra" property, but I cannot find out so far why that is in the codebase.
knowledge_text: A Pydantic Model with a Field(pattern="regex") will raise an "pydantic_core._pydantic_core.PydanticSerializationError: Unable to serialize unknown type: <class 'pydantic._internal._fields._general_metadata_cls.<locals>._PydanticGeneralMetadata'>" exception when calling .model_json_schema() on the class derived with pydantic-partial.create_partial_model - python: 3.11 - pydantic: 2.12.5 - pydantic-partial: 0.10.1 Example Code: ```python from pydantic import BaseModel, Field from pydantic_partial import create_partial_model class Demo(BaseModel): works: str = Field(default="abc", pattern="^a-z$") fails: str = Field(pattern="^a-z$") PartialDemo = create_partial_model(Demo) print("original: ", Demo.model_fields) print("partial: ", PartialDemo.model_fields) Demo.model_json_schema() PartialDemo.model_json_schema() ``` Result: ``` original: { 'works': FieldInfo(annotation=str, required=False, default='abc', metadata=[_PydanticGeneralMetadata(pattern='^a-z$')]), 'fails': FieldInfo(annotation=str, required=True, metadata=[_PydanticGeneralMetadata(pattern='^a-z$')])} partial: { 'works': FieldInfo(annotation=str, required=False, default='abc', metadata=[_PydanticGeneralMetadata(pattern='^a-z$')]), 'fails': FieldInfo(annotation=Union[str, NoneType], required=False, default=None, json_schema_extra={'metadata': [_PydanticGeneralMetadata(pattern='^a-z$')]})} Traceback (most recent call last): File "/tmp/modeltest.py", line 14, in <module> PartialDemo.model_json_schema() ... pydantic_core._pydantic_core.PydanticSerializationError: Unable to serialize unknown type: <class 'pydantic._internal._fields._general_metadata_cls.<locals>._PydanticGeneralMetadata'> ``` If I remove the "fails" property or add a "default" value to it or remove the "pattern" argument, the code works. The issue seems to be that the metadata from the "fails" property is converted to a "json_schema_extra" property, but I cannot find out so far why that is in the codebase.

title: setuptools version 82 breaks the model download and worker start
stack_trace: Today I ran update-runtime.cmd to update my environment. This installed version 82 of setuptools which does no longer provide the pkg_resources module
Startup of horde-bridge.cmd fails at model download because the pkg_resources module is now missing
For now I pinned the version to setuptools==80.9.0 by adding
to the horde-bridge.cmd. Likely there is a cleaner way to do it.
knowledge_text: ### My Operating system Windows ### What did I do Today I ran update-runtime.cmd to update my environment. This installed version 82 of setuptools which does no longer provide the pkg_resources module ### The problem ``` (windows) F:\AI\AI Horde Image>call python -s download_models.py Traceback (most recent call last): File "F:\AI\AI Horde Image\download_models.py", line 3, in <module> from horde_worker_regen.download_models import download_all_models File "F:\AI\AI Horde Image\horde_worker_regen\__init__.py", line 14, in <module> import pkg_resources # noqa: E402 ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'pkg_resources' ``` Startup of horde-bridge.cmd fails at model download because the pkg_resources module is now missing ### Quick workaround For now I pinned the version to setuptools==80.9.0 by adding `call python -s -m pip install --ignore-installed "setuptools==80.9.0"` to the horde-bridge.cmd. Likely there is a cleaner way to do it.

title: Exception ignored in: <function Connection.__del__ at ...> TypeError: 'ABCMeta' object does not support the context manager protocol.
stack_trace: @pcisar Looks like there is still a problem with this. The [current code](https://github.com/FirebirdSQL/python3-driver/blob/master/src/firebird/driver/core.py#L1803):
TypeError: 'ABCMeta' object does not support the context manager protocol
It needs to be adjusted to:
This correctly suppresses the exception and doesn't display the `Exception ignored` message.
knowledge_text: Related #51. @pcisar Looks like there is still a problem with this. The [current code](https://github.com/FirebirdSQL/python3-driver/blob/master/src/firebird/driver/core.py#L1803): ```python with contextlib.suppress: self._att.detach() ``` causes: ``` Exception ignored in: <function Connection.__del__ at 0x000001F220A48400> Traceback (most recent call last): File "C:\Temp\dwdb-workspace\dwdb\.venv\Lib\site-packages\firebird\driver\core.py", line 1802, in __del__ with contextlib.suppress: TypeError: 'ABCMeta' object does not support the context manager protocol ``` It needs to be adjusted to: ```python with contextlib.suppress(DatabaseError): self._att.detach() ``` This correctly suppresses the exception and doesn't display the `Exception ignored` message.

title: MetricCollection.add_metrics doesn't accept another MetricCollection
stack_trace: The `add_metrics` method of MetricCollection doesn't accept another MetricCollection object as input.
ValueError: Unknown input to MetricCollection. Expected, `Metric`, `MetricCollection` or `dict`/`sequence` of the previous, but got MetricCollection(
knowledge_text: The `add_metrics` method of MetricCollection doesn't accept another MetricCollection object as input. ## To Reproduce ```python import torchmetrics as tm def main(): base = tm.MetricCollection({"acc": tm.Accuracy(task="binary")}) extra = tm.MetricCollection({"f1": tm.F1Score(task="binary")}) base.add_metrics(extra) if __name__ == "__main__": main() ``` Output: ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "<...>/repro_issue.py", line 11, in <module> main() File "<...>/repro_issue.py", line 6, in main base.add_metrics(extra) File "<...>/.venv/lib/python3.12/site-packages/torchmetrics/collections.py", line 433, in add_metrics raise ValueError( ValueError: Unknown input to MetricCollection. Expected, `Metric`, `MetricCollection` or `dict`/`sequence` of the previous, but got MetricCollection( (f1): BinaryF1Score() ) ``` ## Package versions - TorchMetrics version: 1.0.3 - PyTorch Version: 2.10.0 - Lightning version: 2.6.1

title: compile-protos fails
stack_trace: I ran `source setup_local_env.sh` and got the following error at the `compile-protos` step.
Ensuring Git LFS files are pulled...
It looks like `setuptools>=82.0.0` (released 2026-02-08) removed `pkg_resources`, which `grpc_tools` depends on.

I replaced `uv run compile-protos` with `uv pip install --reinstall "setuptools<70" && uv run --no-sync compile-protos` in the shell file and it worked. But i'm not sure if this is the best approach. It might need some adjustment.
knowledge_text: Hi, I ran `source setup_local_env.sh` and got the following error at the `compile-protos` step. ``` Ensuring Git LFS files are pulled... Setting up GRPC... Traceback (most recent call last): File "/home/int2/Workspace/gr/alpasim/.venv/bin/compile-protos", line 4, in <module> from scripts.compile_protos import compile_protos File "/home/int2/Workspace/gr/alpasim/src/grpc/scripts/compile_protos.py", line 8, in <module> from grpc_tools import command File "/home/int2/Workspace/gr/alpasim/.venv/lib/python3.12/site-packages/grpc_tools/command.py", line 19, in <module> import pkg_resources ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'pkg_resources' ❌ Failed to compile protobufs. Exiting. ``` It looks like `setuptools>=82.0.0` (released 2026-02-08) removed `pkg_resources`, which `grpc_tools` depends on. I replaced `uv run compile-protos` with `uv pip install --reinstall "setuptools<70" && uv run --no-sync compile-protos` in the shell file and it worked. But i'm not sure if this is the best approach. It might need some adjustment. ## Desktop - OS: Ubuntu 22.04 (x86_64) - Nvidia driver/CUDA version: CUDA 13.0

title: Weather widget crashes YASB when tooltip enabled (ValueError: invalid literal for int() with base 10: '0.0')
stack_trace: When the Weather widget has tooltips enabled, YASB can crash/restart with an unhandled ValueError while updating the label/tooltip. Disabling the tooltip (tooltip: false) avoids the crash.
Configure the weather widget and enable tooltip:
2. Start YASB and wait for a weather refresh (or trigger update).
ValueError: invalid literal for int() with base 10: '0.0'
knowledge_text: ### Windows version Windows 11 ### Windows OS build 25H2 ### YASB version installed YASB: v1.8.7 ### Describe the bug When the Weather widget has tooltips enabled, YASB can crash/restart with an unhandled ValueError while updating the label/tooltip. Disabling the tooltip (tooltip: false) avoids the crash. Configure the weather widget and enable tooltip: weather: type: "yasb.weather.WeatherWidget" options: label: "{icon} {temp}" label_alt: "{icon} {location}: {temp}, Min {min_temp}, Max {max_temp}, Wind {wind}" api_key: "" location: "xxx" update_interval: 600 hide_decimal: true tooltip: true 2. Start YASB and wait for a weather refresh (or trigger update). 3. title: TypeError: can't convert type 'str' to numerator/denominator
stack_trace: The sparkless `F.mean()` function raises a TypeError exception when used on string columns. The pyspark API supports this behavior by interpreting the string as a numeric data type.
During handling of the above exception, another exception occurred:
return result_key, statistics.mean(values) if values else None
for n, d in map(_exact_ratio, values):
TypeError: can't convert type 'str' to numerator/denominator
The pyspark API returns the expected results:
Using numeric types instead of strings allows the `F.mean()` function to work as expected in sparkless
knowledge_text: # Description The sparkless `F.mean()` function raises a TypeError exception when used on string columns. The pyspark API supports this behavior by interpreting the string as a numeric data type. # Version `sparkless==3.30.0` (Commit a6ef5b9) # Example Code ```python from sparkless.sql import SparkSession import sparkless.sql.functions as F spark = SparkSession.builder.appName("Example").getOrCreate() # ================================================= df = spark.createDataFrame( [ {"Name": "Alice", "X": "1", "Y": 1}, {"Name": "Alice", "X": "2", "Y": 2}, {"Name": "Alice", "X": "3", "Y": 3}, {"Name": "Bob", "X": "4", "Y": 4}, ] ) df = df.groupby("Name").agg(F.mean(F.col("X")), F.mean(F.col("Y"))) df.show() ``` # Stack Trace ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "\Python310\lib\statistics.py", line 258, in _exact_ratio return (x.numerator, x.denominator) AttributeError: 'str' object has no attribute 'numerator' During handling of the above exception, another exception occurred: Traceback (most recent call last): File "\scratches\scratch2.py", line 17, in <module> df = df.groupby("Name").agg(F.mean(F.col("X")), F.mean(F.col("Y"))) File "\sparkless\dataframe\grouped\base.py", line 362, in agg result_key, result_value = self._evaluate_aggregate_function( File "\sparkless\dataframe\grouped\base.py", line 1278, in _evaluate_aggregate_function return result_key, statistics.mean(values) if values else None File "\Python310\lib\statistics.py", line 329, in mean T, total, count = _sum(data) File "\Python310\lib\statistics.py", line 188, in _sum for n, d in map(_exact_ratio, values): File "\Python310\lib\statistics.py", line 261, in _exact_ratio raise TypeError(msg) TypeError: can't convert type 'str' to numerator/denominator ``` # Expected Results The pyspark API returns the expected results: ``` Name:string avg(X):double avg(Y):double +-----+------+------+ | Name|avg(X)|avg(Y)| +-----+------+------+ |Alice| 2.0| 2.0| | Bob| 4.0| 4.0| +-----+------+------+ ``` # Workarou

title: PanicException when observer callback raises an exception
stack_trace: When an observer callback raises an exception, pycrdt panics with `SystemError('<built-in function time_ns> returned a result with an exception set')` instead of propagating the original exception. Here is a repro:
from pycrdt import Doc, Text, UndoManager

Error getting timestamp: PyErr { type: <class 'ValueError'>, value: ValueError('Observer exploded!'), traceback: Some("Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "pycrdt/reproduce_bug.py", line 4, in bad_timestamp
    raise ValueError("Observer exploded!!")
") }
note: run with `RUST_BACKTRACE=1` environment variable to display a backtrace

pyo3_runtime.PanicException: Error getting timestamp: PyErr { type: <class 'ValueError'>, value: ValueError('Observer exploded!'), traceback: Some("Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "pycrdt/reproduce_bug.py", line 4, in bad_timestamp
    raise ValueError("Observer exploded!")
") }
My understanding is that the issue involves two code paths:

When an observer raises an exception, `err.restore(py)` sets the exception in Python's interpreter state but execution continues (the closure returns normally to yrs) but then this guy appears (https://github.com/y-crdt/pycrdt/blob/d446e9fd67ae16f993b58f7dcee5e18e489e933b/src/undo.rs#L74):

After the observer runs, yrs calls `Clock::now()` to get a timestamp. The timestamp function calls `time_ns()`, which is a C builtin. When a C function returns successfully while an exception is set in Python's interpreter state, Python raises `SystemError("returned a result with an exception set")`. The `.expect()` then panics.

I assume the best fix may be to protect `PythonClock::now()` from pending exceptions if you still want to call it directly after other exception-setting code or alternatively clear the exception or print an unraisable exception in the callback:
knowledge_text:
When an observer callback raises an exception, pycrdt panics with `SystemError('<built-in function time_ns> returned a result with an exception set')` instead of propagating the original exception. Here is a repro: ```python from pycrdt import Doc, Text, UndoManager def bad_observer(event): raise ValueError("Observer exploded!") doc = Doc() text = doc.get("text", type=Text) undo_manager = UndoManager(scopes=[text]) text.observe(bad_observer) with doc.transaction(): text += "hello" ``` you will get: ``` thread '<unnamed>' (34078) panicked at src/undo.rs:74:38: Error getting timestamp: PyErr { type: <class 'ValueError'>, value: ValueError('Observer exploded!'), traceback: Some("Traceback (most recent call last):
 File "pycrdt/reproduce_bug.py", line 4, in bad_timestamp
 raise ValueError("Observer exploded!!")
") } note: run with `RUST_BACKTRACE=1` environment variable to display a backtrace Traceback (most recent call last): File "pycrdt/reproduce_bug.py", line 14, in <module> main() File "pycrdt/reproduce_bug.py", line 10, in main with doc.transaction(): ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ File "pycrdt/_transaction.py", line 78, in __exit__ self._txn.commit() pyo3_runtime.PanicException: Error getting timestamp: PyErr { type: <class 'ValueError'>, value: ValueError('Observer exploded!'), traceback: Some("Traceback (most recent call last):
 File "pycrdt/reproduce_bug.py", line 4, in bad_timestamp
 raise ValueError("Observer exploded!")
") } ``` My understanding is that the issue involves two code paths: First this code (https://github.com/y-crdt/pycrdt/blob/d446e9fd67ae16f993b58f7dcee5e18e489e933b/src/text.rs#L134-L144) When an observer raises an exception, `err.restore(py)` sets the exception in Python's interpreter state but execution continues (the closure returns normally to yrs) but then this guy appears (https://github.com/y-crdt/pycrdt/blob/d446e9fd67ae16f993b58f7dcee5e18e489e933b/src/undo.rs#L74): After the observer runs, yrs calls `Clock::now()` to get a timestam

title: CLI crashes with 'Operation not permitted' when log file is not writable
stack_trace: When running the `dstack` CLI in a sandboxed environment (e.g., from an AI coding agent), the CLI crashes if it cannot write to the log file at `~/.dstack/logs/cli/latest.log`.
1. Run the `dstack` CLI in an environment where writing to `~/.dstack/logs/cli/` is restricted (e.g., a sandboxed process)
2. Any CLI command fails with a `PermissionError`
The CLI should print a warning about the inability to write logs but continue executing normally, falling back to stdout-only logging.
Wrap the file handler creation in `configure_logging()` with a try-except block to catch `PermissionError` specifically, print a warning, and continue without file logging.
knowledge_text: ## Description When running the `dstack` CLI in a sandboxed environment (e.g., from an AI coding agent), the CLI crashes if it cannot write to the log file at `~/.dstack/logs/cli/latest.log`. ## Steps to Reproduce 1. Run the `dstack` CLI in an environment where writing to `~/.dstack/logs/cli/` is restricted (e.g., a sandboxed process) 2. Any CLI command fails with a `PermissionError` ## Error ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "/Users/cheptsov/.local/bin/dstack", line 10, in <module> sys.exit(main()) ... File ".../dstack/_internal/cli/utils/common.py", line 87, in configure_logging file_handler = logging.FileHandler(log_file) ... PermissionError: [Errno 1] Operation not permitted: '/Users/cheptsov/.dstack/logs/cli/latest.log' ``` ## Expected Behavior The CLI should print a warning about the inability to write logs but continue executing normally, falling back to stdout-only logging. ## Proposed Fix Wrap the file handler creation in `configure_logging()` with a try-except block to catch `PermissionError` specifically, print a warning, and continue without file logging.

knowledge_text: ### Description Two related issues occur when using the imdbinfo library: search_title() may return None, causing an AttributeError when accessing results.titles get_movie() fails with an exception due to an HTTP 202 response from IMDb. --- ### Steps to Reproduce ``` from imdbinfo import search_title, get_movie # Search for a title results = search_title("The Matrix") for movie in results.titles: print(f"{movie.title} ({movie.year}) - {movie.imdb_id}") ``` ``` from imdbinfo import search_title, get_movie # Get movie details movie = get_movie("0133093") # or 'tt0133093' print(movie.title, movie.year, movie.rating) ``` --- ### Error Traceback ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "/xxxx/Documents/xxxx.py", line 5, in <module> for movie in results.titles: ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'titles' ``` ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "/home/xxxx/Documents/xxxx.py", line 17, in <module> movie = get_movie("0133093") # or 'tt0133093' File "/home/xxxx/.local/lib/python3.13/site-packages/imdbinfo/services.py", line 128, in get_movie raw_json = request_json_url(url) File "/home/xxxx/.local/lib/python3.13/site-packages/imdbinfo/services.py", line 95, in request_json_url raise Exception(error_msg) Exception: Error fetching https://www.imdb.com//title/tt0133093/reference: HTTP 202 using User-Agent Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (HTML, like Gecko) Chrome/142.0.0.0 Safari/537.36 ``` --- ### Environment * **OS:** Windows 10 * **Python version:** 3.13.7 * **imdbinfo version:** latest (installed via pip)

ValueError: signalp_org must be one of: other
It seems that `--signalp_org` currently only accepts the value `other`, but not `euk`, which differs from what is described in the documentation.
knowledge_text: ### Report Hello, I added SignalP 6.0 to the annotation using `--run_signalp` which worked fine. When I then tried to change the organism type with `--signalp_org euk`, the run failed with the following error: ``` 2026-02-09 16:47:39,426 - root - ERROR - SignalP annotation failed: signalp_org must be one of: other Traceback (most recent call last): File "/home/justin/.local/share/mamba/envs/dbcan/lib/python3.13/site-packages/dbcan/core.py", line 286, in run_dbCAN_topology_annotation processor = SignalPTMHMMProcessor(config) File "/home/justin/.local/share/mamba/envs/dbcan/lib/python3.13/site-packages/dbcan/annotation/signalp_tmhmm.py", line 22, in __init__ self._validate() ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^^ File "/var/home/justin/.local/share/mamba/envs/dbcan/lib/python3.13/site-packages/dbcan/annotation/signalp_tmhmm.py", line 56, in _validate raise ValueError(f"signalp_org must be one of: {C.SIGNALP_ORGANISMS}") ValueError: signalp_org must be one of: other ``` It seems that `--signalp_org` currently only accepts the value `other`, but not `euk`, which differs from what is described in the documentation. ### Version information dbCAN version: 5.2.7

title: Invalid DRS URIs in lm9 snapshots cause socket.gaierror
stack_trace: When we implemented #3631 we didn't account for the fact that lm9 and lm10 would coexist for a brief period of time. The code we added to support compact DRS URIs in lm10 interprets the [invalid](https://github.com/DataBiosphere/azul/issues/3631#issuecomment-3053352036) DRS URIs in lm9 literally, as host-based DRS URIs. For example, this file
results in a 503 from Azul because `dg.4503` is (correctly) interpreted as a host-name.
for res in socket.getaddrinfo(host, port, family, socket.SOCK_STREAM):
for res in _socket.getaddrinfo(host, port, family, type, proto, flags):

This [breaks](https://gitlab.azul.data.humancellatlas.org/ucsc/azul/-/jobs/91542) the IT so we need to remove the affected snapshot from lm9.
knowledge_text: When we implemented #3631 we didn't account for the fact that lm9 and lm10 would coexist for a brief period of time. The code we added to support compact DRS URIs in lm10 interprets the [invalid](https://github.com/DataBiosphere/azul/issues/3631#issuecomment-3053352036) DRS URIs in lm9 literally, as host-based DRS URIs. For example, this file ``` $ curl -s 'https://service.azul.data.humancellatlas.org/index/files/aacec278-7865-481b-8144-804289286439?catalog=lm9-it' | jq '.files[].drs_uri' "drs://dg.4503/4cd0ae92-d3f0-42c3-8df1-a71f987c9dd1" ``` results in a 503 from Azul because `dg.4503` is (correctly) interpreted as a host-name. ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "/opt/python/urllib3/connection.py", line 174, in _new_conn conn = connection.create_connection( (self._dns_host, self.port), self.timeout, **extra_kw ) File "/opt/python/urllib3/util/connection.py", line 72, in create_connection for res in socket.getaddrinfo(host, port, family, socket.SOCK_STREAM): ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ File "/var/lang/lib/python3.13/socket.py", line 977, in getaddrinfo for res in _socket.getaddrinfo(host, port, family, type, proto, flags): ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ socket.gaierror: [Errno -2] Name or service not known During handling of the above exception, another exception occurred: Traceback (most recent call last): File "/opt/python/urllib3/connectionpool.py", line 716, in urlopen httplib_response = self._make_request( conn, ...<5 lines>... chunked=chunked, ) File "/var/task/azul/http.py", line 153, in _make_request return super()._make_request(*args, **kwargs) # type: ignore[misc] ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ File "/opt/python/urllib3/connectionpool.py", line 404, in _make_request self._validate_conn(conn) ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^^^^^^ File "/opt/python/urllib3/conne

title: [BUG] MultiViewTransform Broken
stack_trace: The validation added in commit fc1f2d2 `if type(batch) is not dict:` Is causing the following error to occur when running the SimCLR on CIFAR-10 readme example.

title: Histogram creation of load collective drops cycles
stack_trace: When converting a load collective to a histogram using `.histogram()` and `.load_histogram()` drops the cycle values.
knowledge_text: ## Description When converting a load collective to a histogram using `.histogram()` and `.load_histogram()` drops the cycle values. ## Reproducible example ```python import pandas as pd import pylife.stress collective = pd.DataFrame( { "from": [300.0, -150.0, -250.0], "to": [-300.0, -150.0, 250.0], "cycles": [1e0, 1e1, 1e2], } ) histogram = collective.load_collective.histogram(bins=3).to_pandas() # Same for # histogram = collective.load_collective.range_histogram(bins=3).to_pandas() print(histogram.sum(), collective.cycles.sum()) assert histogram.sum() == collective.cycles.sum() ``` ## Expected result The assertion should not fail. ## Observed result The assertion fails with ``` 3.0 111.0 Traceback (most recent call last): File "/tmp/mst.py", line 17, in <module> assert histogram.sum() == collective.cycles.sum() ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ AssertionError ``` ## Environment - OS: Ubuntu 24.04 - Version: current dev

title: threads list crashes on legacy branch state with 'messages' key
stack_trace: `bsky threads list` crashes when legacy branch objects in state contain a `messages` key.
branches = {k: Branch.from_dict(v) for k, v in d.get("branches", {}).items()}
TypeError: Branch.__init__() got an unexpected keyword argument 'messages'
`threads list` should tolerate extra/legacy keys in persisted state (or migrate them) and print tracked threads without crashing.
Likely a backward-compat path needed in `Branch.from_dict` (ignore unknown keys like `messages`) or in state migration/normalization before model construction.
knowledge_text: ## Summary `bsky threads list` crashes when legacy branch objects in state contain a `messages` key. ## Repro ```bash cd ~/projects/bsky-cli uv run bsky threads list ``` ## Actual ```text Traceback (most recent call last): File "/home/echo/projects/bsky-cli/.venv/bin/bsky", line 10, in <module> sys.exit(main()) File "/home/echo/projects/bsky-cli/bsky_cli/cli.py", line 680, in main return run(args) File "/home/echo/projects/bsky-cli/bsky_cli/threads_mod/commands.py", line 584, in run return cmd_list(args) File "/home/echo/projects/bsky-cli/bsky_cli/threads_mod/commands.py", line 127, in cmd_list t = TrackedThread.from_dict(t_data) File "/home/echo/projects/bsky-cli/bsky_cli/threads_mod/models.py", line 79, in from_dict branches = {k: Branch.from_dict(v) for k, v in d.get("branches", {}).items()} File "/home/echo/projects/bsky-cli/bsky_cli/threads_mod/models.py", line 31, in from_dict return cls(**d) TypeError: Branch.__init__() got an unexpected keyword argument 'messages' ``` ## Expected `threads list` should tolerate extra/legacy keys in persisted state (or migrate them) and print tracked threads without crashing. ## Notes Likely a backward-compat path needed in `Branch.from_dict` (ignore unknown keys like `messages`) or in state migration/normalization before model construction.

mismatched parameter names between the custom method and tqdm's expected keyword arguments.
1. Run any CLI command that uses `ProgressBarWithSpinner`, for example:
1. Wait for the command to complete.
1. Observe the error during cleanup when tqdm's **del** is called.
self.sp(self.str() if msg is None else msg)
TypeError: ProgressBarWithSpinner.alt_format_meter() missing 3 required positional arguments: '_n', '_total', and '_elapsed'
knowledge_text: ## Summary `ProgressBarWithSpinner.alt_format_meter()` raises a `TypeError` when tqdm's `__del__` method is called during cleanup, due to mismatched parameter names between the custom method and tqdm's expected keyword arguments. ## Steps to Reproduce 1. Run any CLI command that uses `ProgressBarWithSpinner`, for example: ```bash ./backend.ai session convert-to-image <session-name> <image-name> ``` 1. Wait for the command to complete. 1. Observe the error during cleanup when tqdm's **del** is called. ## Logs/Errors ``` Exception ignored in: <function tqdm.del at 0x781ca5ad5260> Traceback (most recent call last): File ".../tqdm/std.py", line 1148, in del self.close() File ".../tqdm/std.py", line 1302, in close self.display(pos=0) File ".../tqdm/std.py", line 1495, in display self.sp(self.str() if msg is None else msg) File ".../tqdm/std.py", line 1151, in str return self.format_meter(**self.format_dict) TypeError: ProgressBarWithSpinner.alt_format_meter() missing 3 required positional arguments: '_n', '_total', and '_elapsed' ``` JIRA Issue: BA-4276

title: SIGPIPE import fails on Windows
stack_trace: `netaudio` fails to launch on Windows due to an unconditional import of `SIGPIPE` from the `signal` module in `netaudio/console/application.py`. `SIGPIPE` is a Unix-only signal and does not exist on Windows.
from signal import signal, SIGPIPE, SIG_DFL
Guard the import with a platform check:
from signal import signal, SIGPIPE, SIG_DFL
The `SIGPIPE` handler prevents broken pipe errors on Unix when piping output — it's not needed on Windows.
knowledge_text: ## Description `netaudio` fails to launch on Windows due to an unconditional import of `SIGPIPE` from the `signal` module in `netaudio/console/application.py`. `SIGPIPE` is a Unix-only signal and does not exist on Windows. ## Error ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "<frozen runpy>", line 198, in _run_module_as_main File "<frozen runpy>", line 88, in _run_code File "netaudio.exe\__main__.py", line 2, in <module> File "netaudio\__init__.py", line 10, in <module> File "netaudio\console\application.py", line 1, in <module> from signal import signal, SIGPIPE, SIG_DFL ImportError: cannot import name 'SIGPIPE' from 'signal' ``` ## Suggested Fix Guard the import with a platform check: ```python import sys if sys.platform != "win32": from signal import signal, SIGPIPE, SIG_DFL signal(SIGPIPE, SIG_DFL) ``` The `SIGPIPE` handler prevents broken pipe errors on Unix when piping output — it's not needed on Windows. ## Environment - Windows 11 - Python 3.13.2 - netaudio 0.0.10 (installed via pipx)

title: Race condition in supervised_proc.py during agent job termination — ValueError: process object is closed
stack_trace: When an agent job terminates after a room closes, multiple `agent_job_termination` async tasks race to close the same `SupervisedProc`. The first task closes the process successfully, but subsequent tasks fail with `ValueError: process object is closed` because `_send_kill_signal()` doesn't check if the process is already closed before calling `kill()`.
This produces 10-15 ERROR-level log entries per call teardown, which is problematic for log-based monitoring/alerting.
The above exception was the direct cause of the following exception:
During handling of the above exception, another exception occurred:
Additionally, ~46 seconds after the burst, a follow-up error is logged:
process did not exit in time, killing process
process exited with non-zero exit code -10
1. Start an agent that joins a LiveKit room
2. Have a participant join and interact normally
3. End the call (participant leaves or room closes)
4. Observe 10-15 `ValueError: process object is closed` errors logged at ERROR level within ~15ms
5. ~46 seconds later, observe `process did not exit in time, killing process`
This happens on every single call teardown, 100% reproducible.
Process cleanup should be idempotent. If a process is already closed, subsequent cleanup attempts should be no-ops (or logged at DEBUG/WARNING level, not ERROR).
In `supervised_proc.py`, `_send_kill_signal()` should guard against the process already being closed:
if self._proc and not getattr(self._proc, '_closed', False):
Additionally, `_handle_termination` in `worker.py` could use a lock or flag to prevent concurrent termination attempts on the same process.
- **No functional impact** — calls complete successfully, no user-facing issues
- **Monitoring impact** — ERROR-level logs on every call teardown cause false alerts in log-based monitoring systems (CloudWatch, Datadog, etc.)
knowledge_text: ## Description When an agent job terminates after a room closes, multiple `agent_job_termination` async tasks race to close the same `SupervisedProc`. The first task closes the process successfully, but subsequent tasks fail with `ValueError: process object is closed` because `_send_kill_signal()` doesn't check if the process is already closed before calling `kill()`. This produces 10-15 ERROR-level log entries per call teardown, which is problematic for log-based monitoring/alerting. ## Stack Trace ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "asyncio/tasks.py", line 520, in wait_for return await fut asyncio.exceptions.CancelledError The above exception was the direct cause of the following exception: Traceback (most recent call last): File "livekit/agents/ipc/supervised_proc.py", line 252, in aclose await asyncio.wait_for(...) title: Missing requires-python in pyproject.toml allows installation on unsupported Python versions
stack_trace: csvkit 2.2.0 uses Python 3.8+ syntax (the walrus operator `:=` in `cleanup.py`), but the package metadata doesn't declare a Python version requirement. This allows the package to install successfully on older Python versions, then fail at runtime with a `SyntaxError`:
if empty_columns := [i for i, count in enumerate(empty_counts) if count == row_count]:
The classifiers in pyproject.toml list Python 3.10+ as supported, but resolvers like pip and uv don't use classifiers for dependency resolution—they rely on the `requires-python` field.
Add `requires-python` to the `[project]` table in pyproject.toml:
requires-python = ">=3.10"  # or whatever the intended minimum is
This will cause resolvers to either select an older compatible version or reject installation on unsupported Python versions, rather than silently installing and failing at runtime.
[This bug report was drafted using AI tools]
knowledge_text: csvkit 2.2.0 uses Python 3.8+ syntax (the walrus operator `:=` in `cleanup.py`), but the package metadata doesn't declare a Python version requirement. This allows the package to install successfully on older Python versions, then fail at runtime with a `SyntaxError`: ``` $ uvx --from csvkit csvclean Traceback (most recent call last): ... File ".../lib/python3.7/site-packages/csvkit/cleanup.py", line 149 if empty_columns := [i for i, count in enumerate(empty_counts) if count == row_count]: ^ SyntaxError: invalid syntax ``` The classifiers in pyproject.toml list Python 3.10+ as supported, but resolvers like pip and uv don't use classifiers for dependency resolution—they rely on the `requires-python` field. ### Suggested fix Add `requires-python` to the `[project]` table in pyproject.toml: ```toml [project] requires-python = ">=3.10" # or whatever the intended minimum is ``` This will cause resolvers to either select an older compatible version or reject installation on unsupported Python versions, rather than silently installing and failing at runtime. --- [This bug report was drafted using AI tools]

title: [Bug]: the cmd_list function in cli.py crashes with a KeyError: 'steps' when listing agents
stack_trace: The `cmd_list` function in cli.py crashes with a `KeyError: 'steps'` when listing agents. The function stores the node count with key `'nodes'` but tries to access it with key `'steps'`.
1. Clone the repository and run setup: setup-python.sh
2. Create an agent in exports (e.g., with a valid `agent.json`)
The command should list all agents in the exports directory with their name, path, description, node count, and tool count.
Description: A simple agent that greets the user...
N/A - this is a core framework bug, not configuration-related.
**Root cause:** In cli.py, the dict is built with key `'nodes'`:
But in cli.py, it's accessed as `'steps'`:
knowledge_text: ## Describe the Bug The `cmd_list` function in cli.py crashes with a `KeyError: 'steps'` when listing agents. The function stores the node count with key `'nodes'` but tries to access it with key `'steps'`. ## To Reproduce Steps to reproduce the behavior: 1. Clone the repository and run setup: setup-python.sh 2. Create an agent in exports (e.g., with a valid `agent.json`) 3. Run: `python -m framework list exports` 4. See error: `KeyError: 'steps'` ## Expected Behavior The command should list all agents in the exports directory with their name, path, description, node count, and tool count. ## Screenshots ``` Agents in exports: hello-agent-graph Path: exports/hello_agent Description: A simple agent that greets the user... Traceback (most recent call last): File "core/framework/runner/cli.py", line 434, in cmd_list print(f" Steps: {agent['steps']}, Tools: {agent['tools']}") KeyError: 'steps' ``` ## Environment - OS: macOS - Python version: 3.14.0 - Docker version: N/A ## Configuration N/A - this is a core framework bug, not configuration-related. ## Logs ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "<frozen runpy>", line 198, in _run_module_as_main File "<frozen runpy>", line 88, in _run_code File "/Users/adith/Documents/work/hive/core/framework/__main__.py", line 6, in <module> main() File "/Users/adith/Documents/work/hive/core/framework/cli.py", line 46, in main sys.exit(args.func(args)) File "/Users/adith/Documents/work/hive/core/framework/runner/cli.py", line 434, in cmd_list print(f" Steps: {agent['steps']}, Tools: {agent['tools']}") KeyError: 'steps' ``` ## Additional Context **Root cause:** In cli.py, the dict is built with key `'nodes'`: ```python agents.append({ "nodes": info.node_count, # stored as 'nodes' ... }) ``` But in cli.py, it's accessed as `'steps'`: ```python print(f" Steps: {agent['steps']}, ...") # accessed as 'steps' - CRASH ``` **Fix:** Change `agent['steps']` to `agent['nodes']` on line 434. ---

title: [Codec] TypeError: Expected list, got tuple
stack_trace: Hi, when installing PyAV from source I can trigger this bug (not reproducible on latest version 16.1..0)
So for some reason reassigning ret from a list to tuple doesn't work. Looks like this was introduced with recent cython changes in that file.
This change fixes it for me but you might have a better understanding of why the above fails and can fix it in a better way (I don't know cython)
knowledge_text: Hi, when installing PyAV from source I can trigger this bug (not reproducible on latest version 16.1..0) ``` Python 3.13.11 (main, Dec 17 2025, 21:08:16) [Clang 21.1.4 ] on linux Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information. >>> import av >>> c=av.codec.Codec('libx264', 'w') >>> c.hardware_configs ret [] type <class 'list'> Traceback (most recent call last): File "<python-input-2>", line 1, in <module> c.hardware_configs File "av/codec/codec.py", line 249, in av.codec.codec.Codec.hardware_configs.__get__ ret = tuple(ret) ^^^ TypeError: Expected list, got tuple ``` So for some reason reassigning ret from a list to tuple doesn't work. Looks like this was introduced with recent cython changes in that file. This change fixes it for me but you might have a better understanding of why the above fails and can fix it in a better way (I don't know cython) ```diff - ret = tuple(ret) - self._hardware_configs = ret - return ret + self._hardware_configs = tuple(ret) + return self._hardware_configs ```

- **String**: FHIRPath parser error at 1:2 - Invalid token "string" (IDENTIFIER)
- **Date**: ValidationError, input should be a valid date, but a dict is provided
- For string: FHIRPath parser error at 1:20 - Invalid token "Z" (IDENTIFIER)
- For now(): ValidationError, input should be a valid datetime, but a dict is provided
- String constants are not correctly escaped, causing the FHIRPath parser to fail. Related to #213
- Date and DateTime constants are parsed as FHIRPath types and not converted to FHIR types, resulting in validation errors when assigning to FHIR resource fields.
- The engine should ensure that constants are properly escaped and that FHIRPath types are mapped to the correct FHIR types when used in assignments.
knowledge_text: When using constants in mapping scripts for different FHIR types, the engine does not correctly handle string escaping and does not convert FHIRPath types (such as date, datetime) to the appropriate FHIR types. This leads to parsing errors, validation errors, or incorrect assignment. #### Example script ```python from fhircraft.fhir.mapper import FHIRMapper import traceback engine = FHIRMapper() cases = [ (123, 'Integer'), ("'A string'", 'String'), ("true", 'Boolean'), (3.14, 'Decimal'), ("'@2024-01-01'", 'Date'), ("'@2024-01-01T12:00:00Z'", 'DateTime'), ("now()", 'DateTime'), ] for case_value, case_field in cases: mapping = f""" uses "http://hl7.org/fhir/StructureDefinition/Patient" as target let MY_CONST = {case_value}; group main(source src, target tgt: Patient) {{ MY_CONST -> tgt.extension.value{case_field}; }} """ print() print('='*23) print(f"{case_field}") print('='*23) try: result = engine.execute_mapping(mapping, {}) assert getattr(result[0].extension[0], f"value{case_field}") == case_value, f"❌ Failed for case {case_value} ({case_field})" print(f"✅ Successfully processed case {case_value} ({case_field})") except Exception as e: print(f"❌ Error processing case {case_value} ({case_field}). \nTraceback: {traceback.format_exc()}") continue ``` #### Output ``` ======================= Integer ======================= ✅ Successfully processed case 123 (Integer) ======================= String ======================= ❌ Error processing case 'A string' (String). title: [Bug]: `Thread` crashes when `target=None`
stack_trace: Creating a `Thread` with `target=None` causes a crash when calling `start()`. According to the documentation, passing `target=None` is valid.
It would be reasonable to handle this case in a way consistent with Python’s standard library threading.Thread, where target=None is allowed and does not cause a crash.
TypeError: run() missing 1 required positional argument
knowledge_text: ### Bug Description Creating a `Thread` with `target=None` causes a crash when calling `start()`. According to the documentation, passing `target=None` is valid. It would be reasonable to handle this case in a way consistent with Python’s standard library threading.Thread, where target=None is allowed and does not cause a crash. ### Version llama_index_core==0.14.13 ### Steps to Reproduce ```python from llama_index.core.types import Thread thread = Thread( target=None, name="null_thread", daemon=None ) thread.start() thread.join() ``` ### Relevant Logs/Tracbacks ```shell Exception in thread null_thread: Traceback (most recent call last): File ".../threading.py", line 1016, in _bootstrap_inner self.run() File ".../threading.py", line 953, in run self._target(*self._args, **self._kwargs) TypeError: run() missing 1 required positional argument ```

title: ASE calculator missing "energy" causes training workflow to fail

knowledge_text: ## Bug Description During training using the PFD workflow, the job fails because the ASE calculator does not provide the "energy" property. title: sphinx.ext.autodoc.mock is a module and not callable
stack_trace: When the sphinx_autodoc_typehints extension is also used, no output is produced for:
from "mymodule.cli". The following exception was raised:
looking for now-outdated files... none found

I have tried this on the most recent versions of sphinx, sphinx_autodoc_typehints, sphinx-click, and sphinx-autobuild and suspect it has something to do with the interaction between sphinx-click and .
I was able to create a minimal example of this bug:
knowledge_text: When the sphinx_autodoc_typehints extension is also used, no output is produced for: ```rst .. click:: mymodule.cli:main :prog: mymodule :nested: full ``` With the error message: ``` reading sources... [100%] index /path/to/repo/docs/index.rst:6: ERROR: Failed to import "main" from "mymodule.cli". The following exception was raised: Traceback (most recent call last): File "/path/to/repo/.venv/lib/python3.14/site-packages/sphinx_click/ext.py", line 459, in _load_module with mock(self.env.config.sphinx_click_mock_imports): ~~~~^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ TypeError: 'module' object is not callable [docutils] looking for now-outdated files... none found ``` I have tried this on the most recent versions of sphinx, sphinx_autodoc_typehints, sphinx-click, and sphinx-autobuild and suspect it has something to do with the interaction between sphinx-click and . I was able to create a minimal example of this bug: [issue-sphinx-click.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/24855672/issue-sphinx-click.zip) Kind regards!

title: Config parser fails on scientific notation for large integers
stack_trace: ### If "Other Airflow 3 version" selected, which one?
While deploying Airflow through a Helm chart, I used the following configuration options:
Upon checking the deployment, I discovered that DAG parsing was failing with errors.
ValueError: invalid literal for int() with base 10: '4.096e+07'
During handling of the above exception, another exception occurred:
airflow.exceptions.AirflowConfigException: Failed to convert value to int. Please check "max_templated_field_length" key in "core" section. Current value: "4.096e+07".

After investigation, I found that the generated airflow.cfg had the value stored in scientific notation format. This type conversion from integer to float occurred during the Helm template rendering process, and the value was already converted when it was stored in the ConfigMap.
### What you think should happen instead?
The config parsing should handle large integer type inputs properly.
deploy the airflow using Helm chart with the option (large interger type input in config)
### Are you willing to submit PR?
- [x] Yes I am willing to submit a PR!
- [x] I agree to follow this project's [Code of Conduct](https://github.com/apache/airflow/blob/main/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md)
knowledge_text: ### Apache Airflow version 3.1.6 ### If "Other Airflow 3 version" selected, which one? _No response_ ### What happened? While deploying Airflow through a Helm chart, I used the following configuration options: ``` config: core: max_templated_field_length: 40960000 ``` Upon checking the deployment, I discovered that DAG parsing was failing with errors. ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "/home/airflow/.local/lib/python3.12/site-packages/airflow/configuration.py", line 1220, in getint return int(val) ^^^^^^^^ ValueError: invalid literal for int() with base 10: '4.096e+07' During handling of the above exception, another exception occurred: Traceback (most recent call last): File "/home/airflow/.local/lib/python3.12/site-packages/airflow/serialization/helpers.py", line 64, in serialize_template_field max_length = conf.getint("core", "max_templated_field_length") ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ File "/home/airflow/.local/lib/python3.12/site-packages/airflow/configuration.py", line 1222, in getint raise AirflowConfigException( airflow.exceptions.AirflowConfigException: Failed to convert value to int. Please check "max_templated_field_length" key in "core" section. Current value: "4.096e+07". ``` After investigation, I found that the generated airflow.cfg had the value stored in scientific notation format. This type conversion from integer to float occurred during the Helm template rendering process, and the value was already converted when it was stored in the ConfigMap. ``` [core] max_templated_field_length = 4.096e+07 ``` ### What you think should happen instead? The config parsing should handle large integer type inputs properly. ### How to reproduce deploy the airflow using Helm chart with the option (large interger type input in config) ``` config: core: max_templated_field_length: 40960000 ``` ### Operating System docker image ### Versions of Apache Airflow Providers _No response_ ### Deployment Official Apache Airflow Helm Chart ### Deplo

❯ uv run --python 3.14 --with absl-py python -c "from absl.flags._helpers import text_wrap; text_wrap('hello')"
Thanks to @hoolean for finding the fix.
knowledge_text: Reproducer, using https://github.com/astral-sh/uv/ for a one-liner: ``` ❯ uv run --python 3.14 --with absl-py python -c "from absl.flags._helpers import text_wrap; text_wrap('hello')" Traceback (most recent call last): File "<string>", line 1, in <module> from absl.flags._helpers import text_wrap; text_wrap('hello') ~~~~~~~~~^^^^^^^^^ File "/.../lib/python3.14/site-packages/absl/flags/_helpers.py", line 274, in text_wrap length = get_help_width() File "/.../lib/python3.14/site-packages/absl/flags/_helpers.py", line 176, in get_help_width data = fcntl.ioctl(sys.stdout, termios.TIOCGWINSZ, b'1234') SystemError: buffer overflow ``` Fix: https://lists.openembedded.org/g/bitbake-devel/message/18351 Thanks to @hoolean for finding the fix.

title: Error after update netbox to version 4.5.1
stack_trace: Hello, after updating NetBox to version 4.5.1, the following error appears when running the script:
TypeError: 'in <string>' requires string as left operand, not NoneType
For now, I've temporarily modified the code to work around this issue:
distro_version and distro_version not in platform:
knowledge_text: Hello, after updating NetBox to version 4.5.1, the following error appears when running the script: ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "/opt/scripts/netbox-sync/./netbox-sync.py", line 146, in <module> main() File "/opt/scripts/netbox-sync/./netbox-sync.py", line 111, in main source.apply() File "/opt/scripts/netbox-sync/module/sources/vmware/connection.py", line 399, in apply view_details.get("view_handler")(obj) File "/opt/scripts/netbox-sync/module/sources/vmware/connection.py", line 2200, in add_virtual_machine detailed_data_dict.get("distroVersion") not in platform: TypeError: 'in <string>' requires string as left operand, not NoneType ``` For now, I've temporarily modified the code to work around this issue: ``` distro_version = detailed_data_dict.get("distroVersion", "") if detailed_data_dict.get("familyName", "").lower() == "linux" and \ distro_version and distro_version not in platform: platform = f'{platform} {distro_version}' ```

title: Signal.levels deprecation warning refers to non-existant Signal.leq_levels
stack_trace: DeprecationWarning: Signal.levels is deprecated. Use Signal.fast_levels, Signal.slow_levels (for "weighting") or Signal.leq_levels (for "average") instead.
AttributeError: 'Signal' object has no attribute 'leq_levels'. Did you mean: 'plot_levels'?
Signal.leq_levels does not exist. That missing method was probably meant to be added with https://github.com/Universite-Gustave-Eiffel/acoustic-toolbox/pull/44 but forgotten.
knowledge_text: `non_existant_leq_levels.py` ``` import acoustic_toolbox as at import numpy as np fs = 48000 y = at.Signal(np.ones(1 * fs), fs=fs) levels = y.levels() leq_levels = y.leq_levels() ``` Output ``` DeprecationWarning: Signal.levels is deprecated. Use Signal.fast_levels, Signal.slow_levels (for "weighting") or Signal.leq_levels (for "average") instead. levels = y.levels() Traceback (most recent call last): File "path\to\non_existant_leq_levels.py", line 7, in <module> leq_levels = y.leq_levels() ^^^^^^^^^^^^ AttributeError: 'Signal' object has no attribute 'leq_levels'. Did you mean: 'plot_levels'? ``` Signal.leq_levels does not exist. That missing method was probably meant to be added with https://github.com/Universite-Gustave-Eiffel/acoustic-toolbox/pull/44 but forgotten.
