title: Silent 'failure' of `__setitem__` with out-of-range indices
stack_trace: An `IndexError` is raised if a user attempts to index with an inappropriate index or indices a Field's data (as supported as a method via the Field directly in cf-python but not in cfdm, it seems) in the context of `__getitem__`, but for `__setitem__` there is no indication that anything is wrong:
>>> # Apply out-of-range hence invalid index with a 'get item'
IndexError: Index [(slice(0, 1, 1), slice(100, 101, 1))] selects no elements from data with shape (5, 8)
>>> # Apply out-of-range hence invalid index with a 'set item', noting no error
>>> # Works (in that the call runs without error, but does nothing)!

So the question is: **should we raise also an `IndexError` for `__setitem__` as for `__getitem__` with invalid indices**? I would argue we _should_, as it gives consistent behaviour across those two related methods, and it prevents the chance of confusion as to why item setting didn't seem to work when the user doesn't realise the indexes are not valid (like myself, see below!). And as for the argument of 'what does NumPy / the Python Array API Standard do / say we should do, indeed they raise the `IndexError` in both cases:
IndexError: index 100 is out of bounds for axis 1 with size 8
IndexError: index 100 is out of bounds for axis 1 with size 8
As noticed when I wasn't using my brain and couldn't work out why masking wasn't being applied with `f[0, 8] = cf.masked` on the first example field which has shape `(5, 8)`.
knowledge_text: An `IndexError` is raised if a user attempts to index with an inappropriate index or indices a Field's data (as supported as a method via the Field directly in cf-python but not in cfdm, it seems) in the context of `__getitem__`, but for `__setitem__` there is no indication that anything is wrong: ```python >>> f = cfdm.example_field(0) >>> f.shape (5, 8) >>> # Apply out-of-range hence invalid index with a 'get item' >>> f.data[0, 100] Traceback (most recent call last): ... raise IndexError( IndexError: Index [(slice(0, 1, 1), slice(100, 101, 1))] selects no elements from data with shape (5, 8) >>> # Apply out-of-range hence invalid index with a 'set item', noting no error >>> f.data[0, 100] = 0 >>> # Works (in that the call runs without error, but does nothing)! ``` So the question is: **should we raise also an `IndexError` for `__setitem__` as for `__getitem__` with invalid indices**? I would argue we _should_, as it gives consistent behaviour across those two related methods, and it prevents the chance of confusion as to why item setting didn't seem to work when the user doesn't realise the indexes are not valid (like myself, see below!). And as for the argument of 'what does NumPy / the Python Array API Standard do / say we should do, indeed they raise the `IndexError` in both cases: ```python >>> a = np.ones((5, 8)) >>> a[0, 100] Traceback (most recent call last): File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module> IndexError: index 100 is out of bounds for axis 1 with size 8 >>> a[0, 100] = 0 Traceback (most recent call last): File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module> IndexError: index 100 is out of bounds for axis 1 with size 8 ``` As noticed when I wasn't using my brain and couldn't work out why masking wasn't being applied with `f[0, 8] = cf.masked` on the first example field which has shape `(5, 8)`.

title: fnctl not compatible with windows
stack_trace: Prøvede at bruge `agr` på Windows, men får en fejl angående fcntl:
from agr.sdk import Skill, SkillInfo, cache, list_skills, skill_info
Found the issue. agr appears to be a third-party tool for managing Claude Code skills, but it's not compatible with Windows.
fcntl is a Unix-only Python module for file locking that doesn't exist on Windows. The agr package wasn't designed to work on Windows.
knowledge_text: Prøvede at bruge `agr` på Windows, men får en fejl angående fcntl: ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "<frozen runpy>", line 198, in _run_module_as_main File "<frozen runpy>", line 88, in _run_code File "C:\Users\shbo\AppData\Roaming\Python\Python313\Scripts\agr.exe\__main__.py", line 4, in <module> from agr.main import app File "C:\Users\shbo\AppData\Roaming\Python\Python313\site-packages\agr\__init__.py", line 5, in <module> from agr.sdk import Skill, SkillInfo, cache, list_skills, skill_info File "C:\Users\shbo\AppData\Roaming\Python\Python313\site-packages\agr\sdk\__init__.py", line 16, in <module> from agr.sdk.cache import cache File "C:\Users\shbo\AppData\Roaming\Python\Python313\site-packages\agr\sdk\cache.py", line 14, in <module> import fcntl ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'fcntl' ``` Min claude code siger: Found the issue. agr appears to be a third-party tool for managing Claude Code skills, but it's not compatible with Windows. The error shows: ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'fcntl' fcntl is a Unix-only Python module for file locking that doesn't exist on Windows. The agr package wasn't designed to work on Windows.

title: Cannot resubmit failed jobs while other jobs are running
stack_trace: Running `babs submit` to resubmit failed jobs when any jobs from the same project are still running causes BABS to raise and exit without submitting anything:
Exception: There are still jobs running. Please wait for them to finish or cancel them. Current running jobs:
So we can't resubmit only failed jobs until every running job has finished (or been cancelled).

When there are still running jobs, resubmit only jobs that are not currently running or pending. That is, only submit failed, cancelled, or never started jobs, and list the job IDs that were skipped because they are still running/pending.
<!--Do you have any ideas about the implementation?-->
knowledge_text: ## Summary Current behavior Running `babs submit` to resubmit failed jobs when any jobs from the same project are still running causes BABS to raise and exit without submitting anything: ``` Traceback (most recent call last): File "/cbica/projects/pennlinc_hcpd/miniforge3/bin/babs", line 8, in <module> sys.exit(_main()) ^^^^^^^ File "/gpfs/fs001/cbica/projects/pennlinc_hcpd/software/babs/babs/cli.py", line 737, in _main options.func(**args) File "/gpfs/fs001/cbica/projects/pennlinc_hcpd/software/babs/babs/cli.py", line 409, in babs_submit_main babs_proj.babs_submit(count=count, submit_df=df_job_specified) File "/gpfs/fs001/cbica/projects/pennlinc_hcpd/software/babs/babs/interaction.py", line 42, in babs_submit raise Exception( Exception: There are still jobs running. Please wait for them to finish or cancel them. Current running jobs: ``` So we can't resubmit only failed jobs until every running job has finished (or been cancelled). ## Additional details Desired behavior When there are still running jobs, resubmit only jobs that are not currently running or pending. That is, only submit failed, cancelled, or never started jobs, and list the job IDs that were skipped because they are still running/pending. ## Next steps <!--Do you have any ideas about the implementation?-->

title: tedee integration deletes webhook on bridge on disable/enable
stack_trace: I'm setting up some Tedee locks on HA and I noticed that the integration deletes the webhooks if it is disabled and enabled again.
1. Set up the lock/door sensor/bridge combo with the Tedee app
2. Add the Tedee bridge to HA (with IP address and API key)
3. Checking `/v1.0/callback` on the bridge shows the webhook existing, according to HA logs it works OK (there is another bug that I will report here, but in general the webhook works)
4. disable the hub added in step 2 (disabling only the bridge device does not trigger this bug)
5. callback still exists in the bridge (and HA still receives events)
The last step should delete and recreate the webhooks, but I see this in the logs:
homeassistant  | 2026-02-03 00:35:56.359 ERROR (MainThread) [homeassistant] Error doing job: Task exception was never retrieved (task: None)
homeassistant  |     raise ValueError("Handler is already defined!")
homeassistant  | ValueError: Handler is already defined!
The only solution is to delete the hub and add it back again. Running reconfigure returns the same error and doesn't add the webhook to the bridge.
### What version of Home Assistant Core has the issue?
### What was the last working version of Home Assistant Core?
### What type of installation are you running?
### Link to integration documentation on our website
### Anything in the logs that might be useful for us?
knowledge_text: ### The problem Hello, I'm setting up some Tedee locks on HA and I noticed that the integration deletes the webhooks if it is disabled and enabled again. Steps to reproduce: 1. Set up the lock/door sensor/bridge combo with the Tedee app 2. Add the Tedee bridge to HA (with IP address and API key) 3. Checking `/v1.0/callback` on the bridge shows the webhook existing, according to HA logs it works OK (there is another bug that I will report here, but in general the webhook works) 4. disable the hub added in step 2 (disabling only the bridge device does not trigger this bug) 5. callback still exists in the bridge (and HA still receives events) 6. enable the hub back The last step should delete and recreate the webhooks, but I see this in the logs: ``` homeassistant | 2026-02-03 00:35:56.359 DEBUG (MainThread) [aiotedee.tedee_client] Webhooks deleted successfully. homeassistant | 2026-02-03 00:35:56.359 ERROR (MainThread) [homeassistant] Error doing job: Task exception was never retrieved (task: None) homeassistant | Traceback (most recent call last): homeassistant | File "/usr/src/homeassistant/homeassistant/components/tedee/__init__.py", line 74, in register_webhook homeassistant | webhook_register( homeassistant | ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^ homeassistant | hass, homeassistant | ^^^^^ homeassistant | ...<4 lines>... homeassistant | allowed_methods=[METH_POST], homeassistant | ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ homeassistant | ) homeassistant | ^ homeassistant | File "/usr/src/homeassistant/homeassistant/components/webhook/__init__.py", line 54, in async_register homeassistant | raise ValueError("Handler is already defined!") homeassistant | ValueError: Handler is already defined! ``` The only solution is to delete the hub and add it back again. title: UnboundLocalError for appearance_stream_obj when doing update_page_form_field_values with flatten in 6.2.0
stack_trace: When upgrading to 6.2.0 I noticed there was an UnboundLocalError when processing a pdf with a `/Sig` field. It does produce a warning 'Signature forms not implemented yet' but I didn't expect it to crash
This is the complete traceback I see:
if flatten and appearance_stream_obj is not None:
UnboundLocalError: cannot access local variable 'appearance_stream_obj' where it is not associated with a value
knowledge_text: When upgrading to 6.2.0 I noticed there was an UnboundLocalError when processing a pdf with a `/Sig` field. It does produce a warning 'Signature forms not implemented yet' but I didn't expect it to crash ## Environment ```bash $ python -m platform Linux-6.8.0-90-generic-x86_64-with-glibc2.39 $ python -c "import pypdf;print(pypdf._debug_versions)" pypdf==6.6.2, crypt_provider=('local_crypt_fallback', '0.0.0'), PIL=12.1.0 ``` ## Code + PDF ```python import io import pypdf writer = pypdf.PdfWriter(io.BytesIO(open("minimal_signature.pdf", "rb").read())) for page in writer.pages: writer.update_page_form_field_values( page, # {"signature": "blah", "date": "xxx"}, {"signature": "ddd",}, auto_regenerate=False, flatten=True ) writer.write(open("op.pdf", "wb")) ``` [minimal_signature.pdf](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/25212719/minimal_signature.pdf) (this can be added to tests) ## Traceback This is the complete traceback I see: ``` Signature forms not implemented yet Traceback (most recent call last): File "/home/johnsharp/scratch/pypdftest.py", line 7, in <module> writer.update_page_form_field_values( File "/home/johnsharp/code/pypdf/pypdf/_writer.py", line 1067, in update_page_form_field_values if flatten and appearance_stream_obj is not None: ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ UnboundLocalError: cannot access local variable 'appearance_stream_obj' where it is not associated with a value ```
